[3] Canada (Alberta Province)
Date: Mon 23 May 2022 7:43 PM CEST
Source: CTVNews Calgary [edited]
https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/1-of-3-alberta-children-hospitalized-with-severe-acute-hepatitis-has-been-released-1.5915192


Officials said on Monday [23 May 2022] that 3 children in Alberta have now been hospitalized suffering from severe acute hepatitis not caused by known hepatitis viruses. None of the hospitalizations in Alberta has required a liver transplant and 1 of the children has since been treated and released.

A total of 10 children in Canada have been found to be suffering from the condition. 3 cases were in Alberta, 2 in Manitoba, 4 in Ontario, and 1 in Quebec. The children were between the ages of 1 and 13 years old.

All children were hospitalized after becoming sick between 3 Nov 2021, and 23 Apr 2022. 2 children have required a liver transplant.

The cases of severe acute hepatitis were not caused by known hepatitis viruses, such as hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E, according to the Public Health Agency of Canada. The agency also said they are analyzing data to see if these reports represent an increase in the frequency of cases of severe acute hepatitis in children not caused by known hepatitis viruses.

PHAC says it's working with provinces and territories to identify cases dating back to October 2021 to match the WHO's own investigation into severe acute hepatitis in children. PHAC added its investigation has been broad, including any children with inflammation of the liver where a cause is not certain.

[Byline: Dave Dormer]

